column4: <content>For St. Christopher. To be placed with early doubtful Bruegels? Photo needed. Glück, Art Quarterly, Winter 1950, p. 44. Look up. In a good state of preservation St Christopher in Store Room of Kh. Mus. Vienna, where it was first attributed to Bruegel himself: It is almost entirely a landscape in daylight, with a big [onleesbaar]-land occupying most of the space same sailing boats in the slightly ? water and a few buildings in the distant background. Only in the right corner is the Saint to be seen in a red cloak, wading through the waves. (26) Engerth nr. 750; cat 1907, N° 663. Published by Fred. C. WILLIS, Niederländische Marine-Malerei, Leipzig [Klinkhardt & Biermann], 1911, p. 10, pl. II, Baldass attrib. to Mathys Cock (pl. XXXIV), 1910 , p. 146, n.4) has been revoked by its author (Zeitschrift für bildende Kunst, 1927, p. 92) without suggesting another name.</content>
